  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 3.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "For he built up again the high places which Hezekiah his father had destroyed",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 18:4, 22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). On the high-place worship, see the comment upon ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 14:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It is quite clear that the people were deeply attached to it, and gladly saw it restored. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And he reared up altars for Baal",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " he reintroduced the Phoenician Baal-worship, the special abomination of the house of Ahab (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 16:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 22:53",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 8:18, 27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.), which Athaliah had been the first to introduce into Judah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 11:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), which Joash had put away (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 11:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but which Ahaz (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 28:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") had recalled. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And made a grove",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "an Asherah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or emblem of Astarte (compare the comment on 1 Kings 14:23)  - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "as did Ahab King of Israel",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 16:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and worshipped all the host of heaven, and served them.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The worship the host of heaven, or the entire multitude of the heavenly bodies, commonly known as Sabaeanism or Ssabianism, was an ancient Babylonian, Arabian, and Syrian practice. It had, perhaps, been introduced among the Jews by Ahaz (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). At any rate, it was from the time of Manasseh one of the favorite idolatries of the Jewish people. The stars were believed to guide the destiny of men, and astrology was cultivated as a main part, or even as the essence, of religion. Astrological tracts form an important element in the literature of the Babylonians (see' Records of the Past,' vol. 1. pp. 153-163). The chief objects of adoration in this worship were the sun and moon, the five planets, and the signs of the zodiac. 2 Kings 21:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "ויּבן ויּשׁב, \"he built again\" the high places, which Hezekiah had destroyed (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 18:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), erected altars for Baal and an Asherah, like Ahab of Israel (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 16:32-33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). האשׁרה is the image of Asherah mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 21:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", whereas in the Chronicles the thought is generalized by the plurals לבּעלים and האשׁרות. To these two kinds of idolatry, the idolatrous bamoth and the (true) Baal-and Asherah-worship, Manasseh added as a third kind the worship of all the host of heaven, which had not occurred among the Israelites before the Assyrian era, and was probably of Assyrian or Chaldaean origin. This worship differed from the Syrophoenician star-worship, in which sun and moon were worshipped under the names of Baal and Astarte as the bearers of the male and female powers of nature, and was pure star-worship, based upon the idea of the unchangeableness of the stars in contradistinction to the perishableness of everything earthly, according to which the stars were worshipped not merely as the originators of all rise and decay in nature, but also as the leaders and regulators of sublunary things (see Movers, Phniz. i. pp. 65 and 161). This star-worship was a later development of the primary star-worship of Ssabism, in which the stars were worshipped without any image, in the open air or upon the housetops, by simple contemplation, the oldest and comparatively the purest form of deification of nature, to which the earlier Arabians and the worshippers of the sun among the Ssabians (Zabians) were addicted (cf. Delitzsch on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 31:26-27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and which is mentioned and forbidden in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 17:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In this later form the sun had sacred chariots and horses as among the Persians (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and incense was offered to the stars, with the face turned towards the east, upon altars which were built either upon housetops, as in the case of the Nabataeans (Strabo, xvi. 784), or within the limits of the temple in the two courts (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 8:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", also ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 21:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 33:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Zephaniah 1:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). This burning of incense took place not merely to the sun and moon, but also to the signs of the zodiac and to all the host of heaven, i.e., to all the stars (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 23:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); by which we are no doubt to understand that the sun, moon, planets and other stars, were worshipped in conjunction with the zodiac, and with this were connected astrology, augury, and the casting of nativities, as in the case of the later so-called Chaldaeans.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(Note: Movers (Phniz. i. p. 65) correctly observes, that \"in all the books of the Old Testament which are written before the Assyrian period there is no trace of any (?) star-worship; not that the Phoenician (Canaanitish) gods had not also a sidereal significance, but because this element was only a subordinate one, and the expressions, sun, moon, and stars, and all the host of heaven, which are not met with before, become for the first time common now,\" - although his proofs of the difference between the Assyrian star-worship and the Phoenician and Babylonian image-worship stand greatly in need of critical sifting.)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "This star-worship is more minutely described in 2 Kings 21:4, 2 Kings 21:5. The two verses are closely connected. The מזבּחות וּבנה of 2 Kings 21:4 is resumed in מזב ויּבן in 2 Kings 21:5, and the יי בּבית of 2 Kings 21:4 is more minutely defined in the יי בּית חצרות בּשׁתּי of. 2 Kings 21:5. \"In the two courts:\" not merely in the outer court, but even in the court of the priests, which was set apart for the worship of Jehovah.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "This star-worship is more minutely described in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Kings 21:4",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Kings 21:5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". The two verses are closely connected. The מזבּחות וּבנה of ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Kings 21:4",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " is resumed in מזב ויּבן in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Kings 21:5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", and the יי בּבית of ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Kings 21:4",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " is more minutely defined in the יי בּית חצרות בּשׁתּי of. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Kings 21:5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". \"In the two courts:\" not merely in the outer court, but even in the court of the priests, which was set apart for the worship of Jehovah.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
